https://arstechnica.com/science/2023/10/hydro-dams-are-struggling-to-handle-the-worlds-intensifying-weather/

>Like most of the world‚Äôs 58,700 large dams, those in California were built for yesterday‚Äôs more stable climate patterns. But as climate change taxes the world‚Äôs water systems‚Äîaffecting rainfall, snowmelt, and evaporation‚Äîit‚Äôs getting tough to predict how much water gets to a dam, and when. Dams are increasingly either water-starved, unable to maintain supplies of power and water for their communities, or overwhelmed and forced to release more water than desired‚Äîrisking flooding downstream.

>But at one major dam in Northern California, operators have been demonstrating how to not just weather these erratic and intense storms, but capitalize on them. Management crews at New Bullards Bar, built in 1970, entered last winter armed with new forecasting tools that gave unprecedented insight into the size and strength of the coming storms‚Äîallowing them to strategize how to handle the rain.

>First, they let the rains refill their reservoir, a typical move after a long drought. Then, as more storms formed at sea, they made the tough choice to release some of this precious hoard through their hydropower turbines, confident that more rain was coming. ‚ÄúI felt a little nervous at first,‚Äù says John James, director of resource planning at Yuba Water Agency in Northern California. Fresh showers soon validated the move. New Bullards Bar ended winter with plumped water supplies, a 150 percent boost in power generation, and a clean safety record. The strategy offers a glimpse of how better forecasting can allow hydropower to adapt to the climate change.

>Modeling studies have long suggested that better weather forecasts would be invaluable for dam managers. Now this is being confirmed in real life. New Bullards Bar is one of a half-dozen pilot sites teaming up with the US Army Corps of Engineers to test how cutting-edge forecasting can be used to optimize operations in the real world. Early tests of the methods, called forecast-informed reservoir operations, have given operators the confidence to hold 5-20 percent reserve margins beyond their reservoirs‚Äô typical capacity, says Cary Talbot, who heads the initiative for the Army Corps.

So, we went to the Pride Shabbat service, and it was mostly lovely, except there was a guest speaker who kind of went off the rails (especially for a family event) talking about the recent violence.

#Mazeldon #Poetry

Spirals

The pain spirals
it consumes

those who fight
those who do not

We all see our side so easily
we miss the others

We are changed by our pain
forget love

and the spiral goes around
again
again
again

-----------
The Winning Side

Do not speak to me
of a war with sides
We have always known war
against hate
and intolerance
and oppression
No mater the labels,
The only winning side
is love. ‚ù§Ô∏è

#feminizationfriday

for a long time, makeup was just a fun thing i did in the evenings

i had some reticence to trying new things and exploring, so eventually i decided to drink some vodka and do my makeup while wasted

i have pictures of that time; maybe one day i will release them... they're hilarious :)

... but i had fun!

this was the key: giving myself freedom to fail!

that enabled me to explore various looks and find what i liked or didn't like

#feminizationfriday

one night, drinking and quite wasted, i did some really awful makeup

like big black panda eyes sort of deal

i have a picture of it and i look back on it with cringe...

i went out to get a glass of water and my girlfriend saw me

she didn't know i was doing makeup and she burst out laughing because my makeup was hilarious

this cut me so deep; i wasn't prepared at all for that reaction

she said sorry almost immediately when she saw my reaction

#feminizationfriday

reflecting on her reaction helped me to unpack some of my feelings about makeup

i decided: i do makeup for me. i do not do it for anyone else. i do it to get an effect that i like in the mirror - that's it

deciding this really helped me to untangle patriarchal ideas of beauty from what i was trying to achieve with makeup

are my ideas of what i like to see in the mirror based partly on patriarchal programming? probably

does it matter? i don't think so!

The only thing that gives me hope in reading the sad result that the referendum will most likely fall is that the result is much closer that the pundits seem to have been claiming.

It's disappointing that fear, lies and ignorance has led around 55% of our population to vote No. But fear, lies and ignorance always have an advantage. It's always hard to push for positivity when the negative side just come up with so many different bullshit reasons for doubt.

I think we should actually celebrate that this many people - of the around 96% of non first nations people in Australia - choose to vote yes.

It wasn't 3%. It wasn't 10%. There was a ground swell of people who wanted change. And will continue to want change.

We're going to push for change.

And it's going to be change that can be achieved. It's changes to equal pay and fair work and bargaining agreements. It's changes to fuel efficiency standards and diesel subsidies. It's changes to fossil fuel usage. Changes to get a national anti corruption commission. Changes to housing affordability.

Changes that mean a lot more to a lot more people.

If you think the no campaign has gained anything by this, I think you're wrong.

Dutton is going to be branded as the boy who cried no. Every time he says no it's going to hang around his head like a mummified relic. Every time he disagrees with the government on something it's just going to look like that same old fear lies and uncertainty campaign he's just run. Anyone expect any serious policies from captain no?

Didn't think so...

Lets be real Labor deserve a hiding, that's not what most of us are depressed and angry about. It's the vulnerable NZers who a right wing government will be delivering one too who don't, It's the backsliding on the environment and public services.

This is a different story if search suggestions are replaced with much more violent and potentially traumatizing content. And that‚Äôs exactly what happened over the last week.

It seems like regardless of their interests, TikTok users are dragged into the melange of true and false information as well as war propaganda by TikTok.

The videos one sees after clicking on one of the suggested search strings range from disturbing violent material to Imams talking about the end of the world to people praying for Israel. Most of those videos are provided without any context or explanations and will likely be hard to understand for many German users.

So, while TikTok brags about not having political ads on the platform, it drags users into one of the most violent, controversial and complicated political conflicts of our times by suggesting to search for these topics and not providing any context or help.

Our mod team posted an in-depth reporting about the issues from last month.

Wake up to see the narrative again is turned into, "since you're claiming to not have been intentionally racist or antisemitic, you are now intentionally transphobic"

We're not trying to "win" here, since a small, but vocal group of people with multiple viewpoints seem to want to take everything as proof of bad intent.

I've been quiet on this for the past month, because I realize that me saying anything is seen as a view of the whole mods team (it is not), and anything that I say will fit a pre-existing narrative.

I cannot claim to not be prejudiced; most of it is internalized and is not something that can be removed or ignored.

That said:

  • We are not trying to be intentionally racist
  • We are not trying to be intentionally antisemitic
  • We are not trying to be intentionally transphobic
  • We are not trying to be intentionally transmisogynist

The last one is my bit of editorializing, as most of the transphobia accusations have been leveled that we specifically target trans women, and this disgusts me.

It disgusts me that some (very few, but vocal) members of the trans community try to intentionally divide us up even further in a way that ignores the existence and plights of every other queer experience.

and six month instead of going to therapy.

Something I wish more extremely online people got: a post is an entire thing.

Words lead into sentences. Sentences lead into paragraphs. The composed whole is rich in context. When you try to parse it line by line, you miss that context. In a just world, people who do this would be ashamed once it's pointed out, and re-read for context.

The world we have instead is one where this is often the spark for pile-ons. The first wave goes in for clout. The second wave takes the malicious framing at face value and parrots the original take.

People too far removed to have easy access to the context feel like they have to have a take, and the safe take is the mob's. They become the third wave.

The fourth wave is endless and unrelenting: every time the subject of the pile-on comes up, the framing with the context filed off is brought back up. Each instance becomes a new stone to lob at the target with each iteration even though the whole thing is built on a foundation of lies.

Mastodon.art hosts a lot of great people and artists.

Part of why we tried so hard prior to appease them is the amount of overlap that our instances have. They are decidedly larger than our instance, and the screenshot attached shows how heavily intertwined we are as two of the oldest Mastodon instances.

What I don't understand is if we are so harmful, why was 30 days notice given and not immediate suspension?

Since the discussion started by one of our mods is enough for our entire instance to be defederated, if you want to maintain connections, you'd have to move one way or another.

This is my personal response, not vetted by or confirmed as a unified view from the mods team at tech.lgbt

I've just been here coming on seven years now trying to maintain a space, and getting too upset IRL over perceptions that are being made from spurious claims.

I don't fault anyone for wanting to change instances over this or any other moderation decision. But the claims that all trans people need to jump ship because we are actively transphobic really upsets me. Transphobia is real, exists, and is actively perpetuated in so many places.

We try our best to respond to as well as proactively protect our members from additional transphobia. While nobody is perfect, the twisting of it to say that we are trying to harm our own members is distressing.

Timeline says "containers" and I'm like.‚Ä¶

which containers tho? OCI containers? Specifically Docker containers relying on docker-compose networking? LXC-style containers? systemd-nspawn containers? Heavily sandboxed systemd services? Kubernetes provisioned OCI? Flatpak or snap? A regular distro package manager implementing ostree? chroot? FreeBSD jails? OpenBSD's unveil and pledge? Where's the border to qemu-user?

Like.‚Ä¶ if you're defining a container to be a box that a process can't get out of then something like PrivateTmp in systemd qualifies as that. OpenRC with the cgroups controller turned on qualifies. Technically a user qualifies.

All of these technologies have their very specific place, and the whole point of the original post was making fun of the technologies being often used outside of their specific place, thereby causing more trouble than their use is worth (like running Kubernetes on your single Raspberry Pi at home, or using podman to build OCI images that are effectively the Distro's base image with a single installed application from base repositories that you could've just installed on either the host or an LXC-like container or an OCI container without the distro).

The original post was funny, but I really want people to stop throwing the word "container" around without specifying what they actually mean. If you mean an OCI container please say OCI container. The world you're creating otherwise is one where I wanna put something in an LXC container to separate two independent systems so I can run maintenance on them independently but I get shot down by someone who heard the word container and thought I was going for an OCI container and they don't want to maintain that.

Me and who? ü•∫ü•∫

Getting to this weird stage where, I've heard myself referred to as "they" enough to know that it fits. Its who I am, its comfy, and its freeing. But I've left "he" in all my bios and such, though I do put it second. This is largely because, while I dont feel like it fits me, it doesn't bother me (like being called a man, male, or *grimaces* Mr does).

But its definitely for other people's convenience. And I think that's all just anxiety. I think im so socially anxious that I want to give people an "out", so they don't have to conform to me. I also recognize that with the beard, and my voice its really hard to not immediately peg me as masculine, so I dont bother correcting people.. But... I would tell literally anyone else my favorite mantra: "fuck em", were they in my shoes.

It's been a week since I watched this film. I'm still processing the experience.

This was a Kubrick-Free "sequel" to "2001: A Space Odyssey" (yes! they made a sequel). It was made in 1984 2 decades after the original, and it shows.

I watched 2001 the day before 2010, and I highly recommend it if you want to experience cinematic whiplash.

The best way to describe this movie is "confidently bad". No sane person would attempt to make a sequel to 2001. The strong lack of imagination is my favorite part. I genuinely believe this was an actual writer thought: "2010? huh. that's just like now (1984), only 30 years later!". They even still have the Soviet Union.

"Why report?"

Because this isn't Twitter. I know my instance isn't going to block someone over an innocent mistake. As long as a SWer has carefully read the rules to make sure what they're posting is allowed, it should be fine. I don't think any instance that allows adult content is going to just straight up ban someone for this.

On the flip side, they're coming from Twitter. Twitter! The hellsite. Where 9.9999 times out of 10, anyone @-ing you for any reason is trying to cause trouble.

I don't know how to navigate that. I'm a stranger to them. They're a stranger to me. That's why I think it's better to report: their admins/mods at least have the authority to short-circuit any learned responses developed on Twitter, and hopefully the skill and experience to handle it.

And if they don't, I sure don't!

This isn't an unconsidered position. Several people have come at me assuming I haven't thought this through before making a recommendation.

And that's all it is. Do as you wish.

I'm just going to note re: global blocklists... the best people in the world can run them, and I think we have seen several instances of what I think actually are *really good people running them*, but it doesn't work... *from a sociotechnical-architecture perspective*. It always results in a sword so big that even the best person swinging it cuts an enormously large cut, and then it comes down to a debate of the person wielding the sword, when the problem was really the sword. And I've been warning that the approach to perimeter defense on the fediverse is going to lead to what I've called "the Nation-State'ification of the fediverse" for at least four years, when I wrote up OcapPub https://gitlab.com/spritely/ocappub/blob/master/README.org

And that is *actively happening*.

You'll notice the document actively stops when it gets to the point of solutions and how you implement them. Why is that? It's because the feedback I got, at the time, was that when I tried to explain how I thought things could be done, "that doesn't sound architecturally like something I understand how to build", and I don't blame people, because in a sense web 2.0 architecture doesn't give you anything much better than a sword. So what else are people supposed to do?

It might not be clear but this is why we're building some of the architecture we are in Spritely... a technical foundation where the expression of the kinds of things I was trying to explain are a natural output.

I just learned about nuclear salt water rockets for the first time last week. It's a pretty neat design, using fissile salts dissolved in water to create what essentially amounts to a continuous nuclear explosion in the nozzle.

I'm not sure why the initial design uses 20% enriched uranium instead of Pu-239. Maybe because getting enough of the latter is too difficult without large-scale production infrastructure in place? Not that we necessarily want large-scale infrastructure for producing nuclear weapons material, which both Pu-239 and U-233 are. 20% enriched uranium is not quite weapons-grade, though (using it in an implosion device is theoretically possible, but nobody has tried), and enriching it further is hard, while separating Pu-239 and U-233 from the other products of the reactions that make them is not very difficult.

I wonder if one could make a fusion-fission hybrid design that works similarly, so the propellant could use natural uranium or thorium salts? One problem with D-T fusion is that a lot of its energy comes in the form of neutrons, and absorbing those neutrons to produce heat is hard. Fission reactions also produce a lot of their energy in the form of neutrons, but the most of the neutron energy gets absorbed by the moderator and the fuel, while the neutrons from D-T fusion don't contribute to the reaction. Using them to trigger fission in fertile (versus fissile) materials is a potential way to create a very safe reactor that uses cheap, safe, proliferation-resistant fuels. But I can't find any rocket designs based on this idea.

Another option is "fission fragment" rockets. The idea there is to use a very energy-dense, high neutron cross section fuel like Americium 242m (the m means it's a "nuclear isomer", whose existence I just now learned about!). Am-242m is supposedly proliferation-resistant. The "dusty plasma" design has an exhaust velocity between 3 and 5% of the speed of light and an efficiency of around 90%, so it could get people to Mars in a couple of weeks and could take probes to other stars.

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fission-fragment_rocket#Dusty_plasma

Enshittification isn't merely a form of #RentSeeking - it is a uniquely digital phenomenon, because it relies on the inherent flexibility of digital systems. There are lots of intermediaries that want to extract surpluses from customers and suppliers - everyone from grocers to oil companies - but these can't be reconfigured in an eyeblink the that that purely digital services can.

A sleazy boss can hide their wage-theft with a bunch of confusing deductions to your paycheck. But when your boss is an app, it can engage in #AlgorithmicWageDiscrimination, where your pay declines minutely every time you accept a job, but if you start to decline jobs, the app can raise the offer:

https://pluralistic.net/2023/04/12/algorithmic-wage-discrimination/#fishers-of-men

4/

I call this process "#twiddling": tech platforms are equipped with a million knobs on their back-ends, and platform operators can endlessly twiddle those knobs, altering the business logic from moment to moment, turning the system into an endlessly shifting quagmire where neither users nor business customers can ever be sure whether they're getting a fair deal:

https://pluralistic.net/2023/02/19/twiddler/

5/

Social media platforms are compulsive twiddlers. They use endless variation to lure in - and then lock in - publishers, with the goal of converting these standalone businesses into commodity suppliers who are dependent on the platform, who can then be charged rent to reach the users who *asked* to hear from them.

#Facebook designed this playbook.

6/

Simply sign up, tell us everyone who matters to you, and we'll populate a feed with everything they post for public consumption":

https://lawcat.berkeley.edu/record/1128876

The users came, and locked themselves in: when people gather in social spaces, they inadvertently take one another hostage.

7/

You joined Facebook because you liked the people who were there, then others joined because they liked *you*. Facebook can now make life worse for all of you without losing your business. You might hate Facebook, but you like each other, and the #CollectiveActionProblem of deciding when and whether to go, and where you should go next, is so difficult to overcome, that you all stay in a place that's getting progressively worse.

Once its users were locked in, Facebook turned to advertisers and said, "Remember when we told these rubes we'd never spy on them? It was a lie. We spy on them with every hour that God sends, and we'll sell you access to that data in the form of dirt-cheap targeted ads."

Then Facebook went to the publishers and said, "Remember when we told these suckers that we'd only show them the things they asked to see? Total lie.

9/

"Post short excerpts from your content and links back to your websites and we'll nonconsensually cram them into eyeballs of people who never asked to see them. It's a free, high-value traffic funnel for your site, bringing monetizable users right to your door."

Now, Facebook had to find a way to lock in those publishers. To do this, it had to twiddle. By tiny increments, Facebook deprioritized publishers' content, forcing them to make their excerpts grew progressively longer.

10/

As with gig workers, digital flexibility gave FB it lots of leeway. Some publishers sensed the excerpts they were posting were a substitute for visiting their sites - and not an enticement - and drew down their FB posting.

When that happened, Facebook could twiddle in the publisher's favor, giving them broader distribution for shorter excerpts, then, once the publisher returned to the platform, Facebook drew down their traffic unless they started posting longer pieces.

11/

Twiddling lets platforms play users and business-customers like a fish on a line, giving them slack when they fight, then reeling them in when they tire.

Once Facebook converted a publisher to a commodity supplier to the platform, it reeled the publisher in. First, it deprioritized publishers' posts when they had links back to the publisher's site (under the pretext of policing "#clickbait" and "#MaliciousLinks").

12/

Then, it stopped showing publishers' content to their own subscribers, extorting them to pay to "boost" their posts in order to reach people who had explicitly asked to hear from them.

For users, this meant that their feeds were increasingly populated with payola-boosted content from advertisers and pay-to-play publishers who paid Facebook's #Danegeld to reach them.

13/

Which is not to say that it's obvious we could produce americium 242m economically if only we were willing to reprocess nuclear waste. And in fact all commercial americium 241 comes from nuclear waste processing, though the Am-241 is not directly extracted from the waste. Instead, Pu-241 is extracted for use in MOX fuel, and the Am-241 that accumulates in that is periodically extracted to prevent the Pu-241 from becoming too radioactive to be handled in the MOX plant. So it's a waste product of MOX fuel production. A waste product that costs $1500/gram. A gram is enough for 3 million smoke detectors.

A user will only spend so much time on Facebook, and every post that Facebook feeds that user from someone they *want* to hear from is a missed opportunity to show them a post from someone who'll *pay* to reach them.

Here, too, twiddling lets Facebook fine-tune its approach. If a user starts to wean themself off Facebook, the algorithm (TM) can put more content the user has asked to see in the feed.

14/

When the user's participation returns to higher levels, Facebook can draw down the share of desirable content again, replacing it with monetizable content. This is done minutely, behind the scenes, automatically, and quickly. In any shell game, the quickness of the hand deceives the eye.

15/

This is the final stage of enshittification: withdrawing surpluses from end-users and business customers, leaving behind the minimum homeopathic quantum of value for each needed to keep them locked to the platform, generating value that can be extracted and diverted to platform shareholders.

But this is a brittle equilibrium to maintain. The difference between "God, I hate this place but I just can't leave it" and "Holy shit, this *sucks*, I'm outta here" is razor-thin.

16/

All it takes is one privacy scandal, one livestreamed mass-shooting, one whistleblower dump, and people bolt for the exits. This kicks off a death-spiral: as users and business customers leave, the platform's shareholders demand that they squeeze the remaining population harder to make up for the loss.

One reason this gambit worked so well is that it was a long con.

17/

Platform operators and their investors have been willing to throw away billions convincing end-users and business customers to lock themselves in until it was time for the pig-butchering to begin. They financed expensive forays into additional features and complementary products meant to increase user lock-in, raising the switching costs for users who were tempted to leave.

18/

For example, Facebook's product manager for its "photos" product wrote to Mark Zuckerberg to lay out a strategy of enticing users into uploading valuable family photos to the platform in order to "make switching costs very high for users," who would have to throw away their precious memories as the price for leaving Facebook:

https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2021/08/facebooks-secret-war-switching-costs

And of all the feeds I produce - email, RSS, Discourse, Medium, Tumblr, Mastodon - none is as labor-intensive as Twitter's. It is an unforgiving medium to begin with, and Musk's drawdown of engineering support has made it wildly unreliable. Many's the time I've set up 20+ posts in a thread, only to have the browser tab reload itself and wipe out all my work.

34/

But I stuck with Twitter, because I have a half-million followers, and to the extent that I reach them there, I can hope that they will follow the permalinks to Pluralistic proper and switch over to RSS, or email, or a daily visit to the blog.

But with each day, the case for using Twitter grows weaker. I get ten times as many replies and reposts on Mastodon, though my Mastodon follower count is a tenth the size of my (increasingly hypothetical) Twitter audience.

35/

All this raises the question of what can or should be done about Twitter. One possible regulatory response would be to impose an "#EndToEnd" rule on the service, requiring that Twitter deliver posts from willing senders to willing receivers without interfering in them. End-to-end is the bedrock of the internet (one of its incarnations is #NetNeutrality) and it's a proven counterenshittificatory force:

https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2023/06/save-news-we-need-end-end-web

36/

Despite what you may have heard, "#FreedomOfReach" *is* freedom of speech: when a platform interposes itself between willing speakers and their willing audiences, it arrogates to itself the power to control what we're allowed to say and who is allowed to hear us:

https://pluralistic.net/2022/12/10/e2e/#the-censors-pen

We have a wide variety of tools to make a rule like this stick.

37/

For one thing, Musk's Twitter has violated innumerable laws and consent decrees in the US, Canada and the EU, which creates a space for regulators to impose "conduct remedies" on the company.

But there's also existing regulatory authorities, like the #FTC's #SectionFive powers, which enable the agency to act against companies that engage in "unfair and deceptive" acts.

38/

When Twitter asks you who you want to hear from, then refuses to deliver their posts to you unless they pay a bribe, that's both "unfair and deceptive":

https://pluralistic.net/2023/01/10/the-courage-to-govern/#whos-in-charge

But that's only a stopgap. The problem with Twitter isn't that this important service is run by the wrong mercurial, mediocre billionaire: it's that hundreds of millions of people are at the mercy of *any* foolish corporate leader.

39/

While there's a short-term case for improving the platforms, our long-term strategy should be *evacuating* them:

https://pluralistic.net/2023/07/18/urban-wildlife-interface/#combustible-walled-gardens

To make that a reality, we could also impose a #RightToExit" on the platforms.

40/
#NSFW #male

This would be an #interoperability rule that would require Twitter to adopt #Mastodon's approach to server-hopping: click a link to export the list of everyone who follows you on one server, click another link to upload that file to another server, and all your followers and followees are relocated to your new digs:

https://pluralistic.net/2022/12/23/semipermeable-membranes/#free-as-in-puppies

41/

A Twitter with the Right To Exit would exert a powerful discipline even on the stunted self-regulatory centers of Elon Musk's brain. If he banned a reporter for publishing truthful coverage that cast him in a bad light, that reporter would have the legal right to move to another platform, *and continue to reach the people who follow them on Twitter*.

42/

Publishers aghast at having the headlines removed from their Twitter posts could go somewhere less slipshod and still reach the people who want to hear from them on Twitter.

And both Right To Exit and End-To-End satisfy the two prime tests for sound internet regulation: first, they are easy to administer.

43/

If you want to know whether Musk is permitting harassment on his platform, you have to agree on a definition of harassment, determine whether a given act meets that definition, and then investigate whether Twitter took reasonable steps to prevent it.

By contrast, administering End-To-End merely requires that you post something and see if your followers receive it.

44/

Administering Right To Exit is as simple as saying, "OK, Twitter, I know you say you gave Cory his follower and followee file, but he says he never got it. Just send him another copy, and this time, CC the regulator so we can verify that it arrived."

Beyond administration, there's the cost of compliance.

45/

Requiring Twitter to police its users' conduct also requires it to hire an army of moderators - something that Elon Musk might be able to afford, but community-supported, small federated servers couldn't. A tech regulation can easily become a barrier to entry, blocking better competitors who might replace the company whose conduct spurred the regulation in the first place.

46/

End-to-End does not present this kind of barrier. The default state for a social media platform is to deliver posts from accounts to their followers. Interfering with End-To-End costs *more* than delivering the messages users want to have. Likewise, a Right To Exit is a solved problem, built into the open Mastodon protocol, itself built atop the open #ActivityPub standard.

It's not just Twitter. Every platform is consuming itself in an orgy of enshittification.

47/

This is the Great Enshittening, a moment of universal, end-stage platform decay. As the platforms burn, calls to address the fires grow louder and harder for policymakers to resist. But not all solutions to platform decay are created equal. Some solutions will perversely *enshrine* the dominance of platforms, help make them both #TooBigToFail and #TooBigToJail.

48/

Musk has flagrantly violated so many rules, laws and consent decrees that he has accidentally turned Twitter into the perfect starting point for a program of platform reform and platform evacuation.

49/

Yes, and?

Students very often come to Informed Consent with a 'task: gaining a yes so I can continue the next step' mindset.

As far as they're concerned, the goal of the informed consent process is to gain a 'yes',so you can do the next thing you think is necessary.
According to this mindset, if you propose your intervention and the patient says no... *crisis*! They are wrong! The right answer was yes, I decided that before I asked them yes or no! Anger and confusion!

I have to reframe this situation for students all the time. Informed Consent is not the task of gaining a 'yes' so you can continue with your own agenda regarding what happens to the patient.

It's a fact finding mission so you can *find out* if what you believe is best also suits the patient.

This often blows students' minds, but receiving refusal from a patient and actually writing it down is you doing informed consent correctly.

The questioning step doesn't become void because you couldn't force the answer to be what you genuinely thought would be best for them.

#Arachtober 14: A wasp's progress. Over a few weeks in July, I saw a cobweb spider on a fire hydrant parasitized by a wasp larva, then the wasp's pupal cocoon, then at last the empty cocoon.

Some parasitoid* wasps alter the spider's behaviour to make them spin a web more suited to sheltering the pupating larva; not sure if this was the case here.

There are also hyperparasitoids that target parasitoids, so for all I know the wasp itself may have been parasitized and a different species emerged!

#DailySpiderPic #spiders #wasps #parasitism #Araneae #Theridiidae #Hymenoptera

____
* "Parasitoid" means a type of parasite that eventually kills its host rather than simply feeding on it. Your typical parasitoid is a solitary wasp that lays eggs on hosts which become larvae that devour the host, often from within.

Proposed cocktail for tonight:

Modifying https://www.cookingchanneltv.com/recipes/alie-ward-and-georgia-hardstark/5-spice-on-ice-2120021 to what I have on hand.

Already have:
5 spice simple syrup

Don't have:
fernet
kumquat

Sub:
Green chartreuse, yellow chartreuse, Cynar, or absinthe for fernet
Citrus tinctures of my own making and/or dry curacao for kumquat

Proposed new recipe:
- 1 Tbsp (15 ml) 5 spice simple syrup
- splash (6 ml) Cynar
- 1 Tbsp (15 ml) dry curacao or tinctures to taste
- 3 dashes Angostura bitters
- 2 oz (60 ml) spiced rum
- ice

Shake everything together, pour with nice ice float. Enjoy.

P.S. a "splash" is a little bit more than a teaspoon (5 ml) at about 6 ml. A dash doesn't really have a formal volume equivalent. It's whatever comes out of a shaker bottle.
